item.title: U.S. Sanctions Firms, Tankers It Accuses of Exporting Venezuelan Oil
item.description: The Trump administration on Thursday blacklisted more than a dozen individuals, their businesses and two tankers alleged to have been involved in as much as 40% of Venezuela’s crude-oil exports in recent weeks.

item.title: Macron Meeting With Johnson Kicks Off Coronavirus-Era Diplomacy
item.description: British Prime Minister Boris Johnson will host French President Emmanuel Macron in a rare moment of face-to-face diplomacy since the coronavirus outbreak hit earlier this year.

item.title: Coronavirus Is Taking a High Toll on Sweden's Elderly. Families Blame the Government.
item.description: Discontent is growing over official triage guidelines that critics say too often deny elderly patients vital care.

item.title: Indians Rage at China After Bloody Border Clash
item.description: Anti-China protests spread in India as people vented their anger about the death of 20 Indian soldiers in a brawl between Indian and Chinese forces along the countries’ disputed border.

item.title: Number of Refugees World-Wide Has Doubled in Past Decade
item.description: About 1% of the world’s population had fled their homes as of the end of last year, which includes both refugees and those internally displaced within their own countries, according to a new U.N. report.

item.title: German Prosecutors Say Man Charged in Berlin Murder Was Acting for Moscow
item.description: German prosecutors charged a Russian citizen who they said was acting on the Kremlin’s orders in the murder of a Georgian national in Berlin last year.
